CD 2 has noteworthy technical strengths — transparent, dynamics‑preserving remastering, punchy controlled drums, restrained reverb and clear separation — which are all things I value. However, it is described as “stark, edgy new‑wave” that “rewards focused, front‑and‑center listening” with consistently close‑mic, tactile midrange vocals. That explicit front‑of‑mix emphasis conflicts with my stated dislike of vocal showmanship and my preference for vocals that sit naturally embedded with instruments rather than being pushed forward as the dominant, attention‑commanding element. The new‑wave “angled guitars and layered synths” also point to a sonically forward, possibly aggressive presentation that trades the warm, analog character I gravitate toward for a more clinical, in‑your‑face aesthetic.
Weighing both, CD 1 better preserves the analog warmth, headroom, natural embedded vocals and tasteful, sparse instrumentation I prefer; CD 2, despite good dynamics and clarity, leans into a front‑and‑center vocal and stark aesthetic that runs counter to my dislikes. For those reasons I select CD 1 and reject CD 2.

