Evaluation and reasoning:
- The Expansive double‑LP directly matches the core, highest‑priority items in my preferences: it is explicitly side‑length and multi‑section (exactly the longform, front‑to‑back sequencing I favor), features dense but tightly separated layered electric/acoustic guitars and keys (matches my desire for layered, well‑separated instrumentation), and includes multi‑tracked harmony vocals and expressive solos (both specifically called out in my preferences). Its warm, analogue‑like mastering that preserves transient snap, micro‑dynamics and headroom, plus restrained reverb and spacious imaging, aligns very closely with my preference for analog warmth, preserved dynamics, and front‑to‑back imaging that rewards immersive listening. All of those attributes address my dislikes as well: preserving headroom and dynamics counters loudness‑crush, restrained reverb and tight separation avoid smearing, and an analogue‑like approach avoids glossy, overly processed radio polish.
- The '80s Pop Hits' disc has some attractive technical traits: guitar‑forward intimate mixes, warm tape midrange, transparent low‑compression transfers, close front‑of‑mix vocals, tight stacked harmonies, and snappy natural drums with preserved headroom and microdetail. Those aspects overlap with things I like (guitar forward, warm tape character, low compression, snappy transients, clear harmonies). However, important mismatches remain: it is described as glossy 80s AOR/pop hits—the 80s AOR/pop aesthetic often implies radio‑oriented production choices and an overall glossy sheen that I specifically said I dislike. Even though this release is remastered with low compression, the hits/short‑form sequencing and close, front‑of‑mix vocal placement work against the expansive, side‑length, front‑to‑back imaging and longform pacing I favor. In short, '80s Pop Hits' may be excellent for immediate, lyric‑forward single‑track listening, but it lacks the large‑scale, immersive, analog‑roomy longform character (multi‑section sequencing, dense layered guitars across LP sides, spatial staging) that are central to my preferences.
Conclusion:
Because my principal preference is for immersive, side‑length, multi‑section, guitar‑forward longform albums with dense but well‑separated layers, multi‑tracked harmonies, expressive solos, and analogue‑like mastering that preserves dynamics and spatial depth—and because the Expansive double‑LP explicitly lists all of those attributes while avoiding the radio‑polish and short‑form focus of the 80s hits—I choose the Expansive double‑LP and reject '80s Pop Hits' despite its competent remastering and some shared qualities.

